                        Installing EasySync and using...
                       ==================================

   Be calm. This is a beta version. Read all I wrote before running it... Maybe
it is secure, maybe it is not. It is not my problem anyway if you want to run it
in order to use it. I suggest you to "use" and install it in order to test it.
Read carefully (and be sure to understand the matter) first lines of the first
page of this document @{"->" link "MAIN"}

   To install EasySync, de-archive it where you want to place it. That's all.
This beta version is not ready-to-use. After unpacking the archive, you have to
place EasySync properly... Refer to @{"Package Contents" link "pack"}
Read this document and learn how to use EasySync. Modify prefs file according to
your needs.

   Harmless test (harmless for file integrity) can be done in ram:

@ENDNODE

@NODE "workwell" "Why doesn't EasySync work well?"

                        Why doesn't EasySync work well?
                       =================================

   It should not happen. However it is possible, it's a beta version!

   Check protection flags (EasySync copies protection attributes, but if some
file has "read" disabled, EasySync do not de-protect it...) IMPORTANT: EasySync
beta clear Archive protection bit on updated file.

   Check if the destination dir is or not a subdir of source dir. If it is, the
request you are doing is strange, you can imagine what it happens by yourself.
However it should not be so grave. While I am writing, I have not tested yet
this strange case.

   Crashes: it should not. But I have not checked all "exit point" on error
(yet)... It could be a unknown bug. Before you think it is, check how deep is
the dir EasySync is going to examine. Try to raise EasySync stack. (EasySync has
recursive subroutines, but your hd-tree should be very very deep!)

   EasySync is in beta release, so it does not do all it should do (maybe) in
the future. Read carefully each node of this doc.

   Well, all right about this points? Then, contact me, maybe you have found a
bug I have not imagined!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "requi" "Requirements"

                                  Requirements
                                 ==============

   Any Amiga with at least 68020 and AmigaOS 3.0 (v39).

   EasySync has not huge memory requests, however some of its subroutine are
recursive and very deep paths suck more and more memory and stack. However there
are several "checkpoints" so the worst thing it can happen is that EasySync does
not its job and do not alert you (even if ALMOST each error is told to the
user). Of course this is true if this beta version is bugs-less. But no stack
control is done: each "level" gets from 46 bytes to 60 or a little bit more (for
temporary storages). It should be safe up to 100 levels and more when stack is
8000 bytes. While copying huge files, EasySync check for free mem and allocs a
buffer that is "LARGEST_BLOCK/4" and this buffer is kept for all the time needed
to copy that file. When it has finished it's released and EasySync will ask for
memory again when it needs to. So while copying very very huge files and
your largest_block will be 3/4 of the previous one for all the time EasySync
needs to copy the file (longer time <- smaller largest block).

@ENDNODE

