@NODE "needqm" "When do I need EasySync?"

                            When do I need EasySync?
                           ==========================

   You have to know it for yourself. Read carefully what EasySync does in
@{"What is Easy Sync" link "whateasy"} and in @{"Modus Operandi" link "modusoperandi"}.
Then be sure to understand that this is a BETA unfinished version for testing
and evaluation.

   You need EasySync everytime you want to make two directories the same,
updating an old file in one of the dir with the more recent file in the other
one.

   When it will be a secure version (this is, but I am not so sure...) I can
imagine it could be useful to do a mirror of a site, for example. Net(ftp)
handling should be not requested because it exists a handler-device that
allows to see a Internet (ftp)site as an Amiga device, e.g. you could say
"ftp:ctan.tug.org/" to access on TeX User Group ftp site as it were a dir.
However this is only an oniric example of (maybe possible, maybe unuseful)
usage.

   To say all the truth, it exists a program called @{i}FolderSync@{ui} that seems to do
the same job as mine, to know more about this link to @{"FolderSync VS EasySync" link "foldervseasy"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "foldervseasy" "FolderSync VS EasySync"

                             FolderSync VS EasySync
                            ========================

   We have not too much imagination for file names, have we?

   @{i}FolderSync@{ui} v1.3 is by Chris S Handley in Aminet (util/dir) and (these are his
own words) "allow one set of files to be shared by two separate people
(computers), and occasionally update BOTH people's copies of the files with the
changes that the other has done (this is called synchronisation)."

   Apart from the fact that my dictionary has "synchronize, synchronizer,
synchronization" and so on, apart from the fact that I don't know what people
refer to when they say "spam, spamming" words (it's a wisecrack), FolderSync
seems to do the same job EasySync is written for.

   I must stress the words "it seems", and before I go straight on I feel the
need to specify and stress some facts.

   When I started EasySync I didn't know anything about FolderSync, but I know
something about an operation called synchronization on Windows(TM). The only
thing I have understood of that operation is that at the end it makes two
directories, drawers, folders or how do you want to call them the same, updating
old files and copying non-existing files from A to B and viceversa. (On 24
October I add: Windows(TM) syncronization is very different from what I meant
with that word. It exists offline and online sync-tion, latter seems for site
mirroring or network file sharing without user care for updating, former by now
stands like a non-understandable desert... it seems to me the FolderSync's way)

   EasySync's aim and how EasySync reaches it, should be clear reading this
documentation (@{"Modus Operandi" link "modusoperandi"} is detailed).

   Briefly, you give one or more couples of source and dest dirs, EasySync
compares the contents: if a file/dir do not exist there but exists here, it is
copied and viceversa (EasySync, using DOS, tries also to copy attributes: date
which is fundamental!, protection bits - also that for group and other -,
comment, owner; but the success trusts file system... see below). (IMPORTANT:
Archive protection bit is cleared on updated file!)

   However, my approach to the problem is direct, noodles-less (spaghettiless),
simple: my EasySync know nothing about filesystem incompatibility (Amiga file
system supports comments, name length is 108 maximum - 30 indeed - other file
systems don't support comments, support name length longer than 108 or 30, could
be case sensitive and so on, have more "protection" bit, can have a owner;
owner, group/other protection bits seems to be handled, even if Amiga ignore
them, there's room to store them, but it should be clear that if "Work:Amiga"
has Amiga FFS (or OFS?!) and "Linux:/root/pub/srvcs/Amiga" (EasySync runs on
Amiga of course) has e.g. multiuserFFSforlinuxpartition-handler which handles
multiuser properties and more, and EasySync copy a file from "Linux:..." to
"Work:Amiga", on Amiga side those properties will be lost. Trust Amiga file
system: luckly if it, even if ignoring them, keeps group/other bits and owner
info and if they are senseful for linux-side with a little help by the handler,
then when that file is updated from Amiga to Linux, then its properties will be
saved, luckly... But comments, e.g., will be lost)

   File system incompatibility should be handled by the filesystem itself. Just
to say, it is not a problem if you try to set a comment where you cannot do it,
but you maybe lose that comment and this could be a problem. EasySync is thought
in order to work with Amiga-like filesystem on (hard)disks and other storage
system with a filing system (!), that probably belong to the same Amiga.
Handling NFS, RFS and whatever you can imagine involves proper handler
possession on Amiga side.

   These facts I hope make you to agree with my use of "it seems". FolderSync do
things different from EasySync. Despite of their -Sync name, they are different
tool. But in particular situation they should behave the same (I have not tried
FolderSync, however, I only read its doc). Exactly, they do the same on dirs in
some cases, but their final purpose is not the same. EasySync has no horizontal
pretensions, while FolderSync should be useful (as its doc says) when you have
to sync things on separate computers (so I say horizontally, think about a
network... or a link between two computers)

   If you are not interested in comment, EasySync do synchronize Amiga
filesystem and "FAT" without problem - if the handler for FAT95 has no problem
(exemplum gratia, CrossDOSFileSystem/mfm.device read/write MSDOS W95 style disks
without problems. I haven't tried with hd-partition and fat95 handler, however
if it works or not it depends on the "goodness" of fat95 handler. The problem
will be with too much long names that will be truncated on Amiga side and
comment losses on fat95 side).

   About synchronizing two separate, physically different devices, it is enough
for EasySync you can refer to them by using a name such as "psion7:" and of
course you need the handler which fits your need. You have to hope someone will
write it if you can't find it on Aminet. Synchronizing, e.g., "Amiga:sync1" with
"psion7:back" is problem-less only if the handler which handles "psion7:", and
so the native psion7 filesystem, supports at least Date (my sync is based on
date comparing); then you surely know that you want to sync that dirs, so if
e.g. psion filesystem doesn't support comment, you won't use comment on Amiga
side! Or, use FolderSync instead if it fits your needs.

   VERY VERY IMPORTANT it is to remember that EasySync works comparing dates!
The filesystem should always handle last-update date. I vaguely remember
Unix/Linux has three (3) date, in order to store last-modified, last-accessed
and inode change date/time. However, only last-modified date is interesting for
EasySync (it should be also this kind of date that a linux/unix system shows
when you run "ls mydir") If you are interested in updating file also on
inode-changes, you have to ask for another program, e.g. FolderSync maybe (I
don't know) could fit your needs.

   EasySync do not check if the device it will work on is or not a filesystem. I
will add this "feature" on future version (it is easy, very easy, but I am
thinking about that just know, it's too late for last-moment-adds). Keep in mind
this is a beta version, without a lot of features it will have, check <here> to
know more.

   FolderSync's author is very proud of how well its program handles the matter
and problems due to lack of support of filing system, so I think he resolves all
this problems. Ok, EasySync is meant to work on Amiga-like file system or when
you don't care about protection bits, comments, file names length, even if it
"tries" to preserve all the attributes the filesystem allow. I do not agree with
FolderSync's author about the oration on "The best System" in particular about
open source choice on Linux speech, however this is another tale and won't be
told here.

   If you read (carefully) my doc and FolderSync's doc, you will know more about
differences and understand what you need to solve your problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "whateasy" "What is EasySync?"

                               What is EasySync?
                              ===================

   EasySync is a "software package" (?) to synchronize two directories and their
contents according to the dates of single files. The existing files are updated
if necessary and non-existing files/directories are copied, so that when
EasySync has finished, the directories contain the same files, and more they
contain a backup dir (.prev). In fact according to EasySync, updating means that
recent files overwrite old files with the same name and path, so the old files
are saved in path/.prev/filename. This is not an efficient way to avoid unwanted
updates, anyway the user has to care about this checking its directories after
EasySync-ing.

   The idea is not so complicated. The way it should be done, instead, it could
be complicated. There are several ways you can imagine about this kind of
backupping/updating. I've got one, even if in the future EasySync will understand
(a lot of) flags (now called MODEs) that will change its behavior. Indeed, this
will happen if someone think it could be useful sometimes somehow, or because I
will have no anything else to do.

   Read @{"How does EasySync work?" link "howeasy"} to know/understand more about its behaviour.

   You have to know that the idea for this program is got from a (system)
program on a common popular Operating System, the wide-spread one, which avoid
you to use a common english word because of "trademark/copyright" and so on
(laugh it's a jest), so you should say finestre, or fenõtres, or Fenster, or
vinduer, or gluggar, or ikkunat... instead of using english plural of window.
(If you have two of them, you have to say: close the window, no I changed my
mind, close both ---:)
It's not a problem if you dayly speak not English. I have never used that tool
on that OS, but someone explained me what it does. I am not sure to have
understood its behaviour... This is my own interpretation and fits my own
need. More similar it should be such a FolderSync, link @{"here" link "foldervseasy"} to know about
that program, its author and so on.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "howeasy" "How does EasySync work?"

                            How does EasySync work?
                           =========================

   You can read as it does its job on @{"Modus Operandi" link "modusoperandi"} section.

   First of all, you can run EasySync in two ways. You can use it from CLI/Shell
or script file or run it from Workbench, by doubleclicking on its icon. In both
cases, EasySync can ask for directories or read them from a file called
EasySync.prefs, which should be where EasySync is, or you have to tell it where
it can found that file.

@{fg highlight}From CLI/Shell and scripts@{fg text}

   You can call it without argument. Then, EasySync will open an ASL file
request, using it you will choose first source directory, then destination
directory. After choosing, EasySync will synchronize those directories you
specified and then it will leave. This is syncronous mode. You can specify also
the MODE using MODE keyword (type "EasySync ?" to know about keywords).

   You can call it with HIDE switch. The behaviour is the same as the previous
case, but now it does its job in a asyncronous mode. When it has finished,
EasySync becomes a commodity and waits. You can wake it up pressing HOTKEY or
selecting "EasySync" from workbench menu. In this beta version, these two
actions do nothing. EasySync should also put a notify request on that
directories and/or on their contents, in order to update them every time
something is modified. This beta version does nothing about notification. In the
future it will (maybe) and the real behaviour will depends on how AmigaDOS
handles notification. (I read it does strange things, however I will know more
when EasySync will do it.)

   You can also call EasySync passing "SOURCEDIR" and "DESTDIR" on command line,
with or without HIDE switch and MODE keyword. You have choosen your directories
on command line, but except for this detail, EasySync does the same things as
you have choosen directories via ASL requester, so refer to previous two
paragraphes. @{bg highlight}BEWARE:@{bg back} This beta version ignores SOURCEDIR, DESTDIR, MODE and
everything else when HIDE is specified. All those "options" are taken from
icon... so it should exist to allow EasySync to work. This oddnes will be fixed
in the future.

   Last, you can run EasySync specifying FILE keyword and a preference file. See
@{"here" link "prefformat"} to know more about preference file.


@{fg highlight}From workbench@{fg text}

   You can also run EasySync doubleclicking its icon (it is not so a wonderful
icon, isn't it?). In this case, EasySync reads the tooltype from the icon and
behave accordingly. Default behaviour is to read default "EasySync.prefs" file
in the program directory, to scan it, to synchronize directories (or single
files?) there specified according to the specified MODE and then to become a
commodity, as if you had written HIDE from CLI/Shell. EasySync waits for user
commands: hotkey pressing, workbench AppMenu selection, commodity commands or
DOS notification, that in this beta version is still not coded.

   Use "FILE" tooltype to specify another prefs file, or use "ASK" tooltype to
make EasySync opens ASL requesters, "ONCE" tooltype to avoid that EasySync
stands in memory as a commodity and does notification (which, I repeat, it won't
do in this beta version).

   More, "standard" CX_POPKEY and CX_PRI tooltype are understood. Nowadays
EasySync has not a GUI, but maybe a day it will have, in order to monitor
program status. Note that you can not specify MODE when ASK tooltype is "on".
Because of the fact that MODE is a decimal number which will correspond to a
bits mask that modify EasySync's behaviour, it could be hard for the user write
down the right number, and it has no-sense: it should be a more intelligible
way. Prefs file, even if it is ASCII editable file, should be generated by a
manager program, that will generate for you also the MODE number, while you have
only to click here or there. From CLI, it is supposed you know what you are
doing (maybe I can write a "guimode-to-numbermode" utility, or change MODE
keyword in to a lot of switch), however when you do not specify SOURCEDIR and
DESTDIR you should be able to specify "MODEASK" in order to inform EasySync you
want it to open a window where you can select the MODE by clicking gadget and
not writing numbers... Default MODE is "0", that means, the behaviour I
explained before.

   However this is a beta version and it knows only two MODE: that I explained,
and "backup" mode, which is the same as former, but the destination-to-source
pass is skipped.

   Now, when I say I explained "MODE 0", I mean I have already written the node,
so you can read it @{"here" link "modusoperandi"}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "prefformat" "Prefs file format"

                               Prefs file format
                              ===================

   EasySync preference file is an ASCII file so you can edit it, but it also has
a format you must respect. These are the rules.

   First line contains ";;EasySync;;" (line means it ends with a newline code).

   Avoid blank lines.

   After header, each line is:

   <SOURCEDIR> <DESTDIR> [MODE=nn]

   or

   <SOURCEFILE> <DESTFILE> FILE

   The file must end without trailing lines.

   Each line after the header is read via ReadArgs, with
"SOURCE/A,DEST/A,FILE/S,MODE/N/K" template, so you can write each line also as,
e.g.:

   MODE=1 DEST="back:norge" SOURCE="work:foto/norge"


   However, in the future I will code a preference manager, with simple (I hope)
and usable GUI, to configure (=write) prefs file and to do also (maybe) guided
synchronization.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "modusoperandi" "Modus Operandi"

                                 Modus Operandi
                                ================

   In this beta version, EasySync works in two mode. There are not other modes,
but if you think you need this or that behaviour, tell me.

   If you have choosen directories from CLI/Shell or via ASL requesters,
EasySync has only those directories on which it will work. If you have specified
a prefs file, EasySync probabibly will have a list of couple of directories and
maybe modes for each couple, and it will repeat its job for each couple.

@{fg highlight}MODE 0@{fg text}

   EasySync explores the contents of source dir using ExAll (this is not
important at all, so I will say nothing more about the loop needed to end ExAll
request and I will imagine ExAll fills EasySync's buffer with ALL the contents
of source dir). For each entry, EasySync (from now, ES, it in Deutsch) checks if
it is a file or not. If it is a file, it appends its name to the path of dest
dir and ES checks if the file exists or not. If not, ES copies the file in the
dest dir. If the file exists, ES compares the dates of source and destination.
The oldest is copied in ".prev" backup directory created if it does not exists
in the same dir where the file to be saved lies; the more recent file is copied
and replaces old one. ES beta does not check the consistence of the date; check
your clock before, and be sure when you modified some file the system date was
all right. If the entry is a dir, ES searches the same dir in the dest dir. If
it exists, ES call itself with SOURCE="sourcedir/newdir" DEST="destdir/newdir"
with the same MODE (here MODE 0). Of course, there is a recursive function in ES.
If "newdir" does not exist in the dest dir, ES will copy it.

   This is what I call source-to-dest pass. When it has finished, ES begins the
dest-to-source pass. ES explores dest dir using ExAll. Of course, in both direct
(source-to-dest) and inverse (dest-to-source) pass, the ".prev" directories
are ignored. For each entry, ES checks if is a file or a dir. If it is a file,
ES checks if exists in the source dir. If the file exists, ES looks forward to
the next entry. If the file does not exists, ES copies it from dest dir to
source dir. If the entry was a dir, and if the dir exists also in the source
dir, ES does skips to the next entry. If the dir does not exists, ES copies it
from dest to source.

   Now, regardless of ".prev" dir, source and dest dir are synchronized, id est
they are the same and contain only the most recent files/dirs that were in
common between original source and dest dir and of course both have the
files/dirs which they had not before.


@{fg highlight}MODE 1 (or backup)@{fg text}

   Same as "MODE 0", but inverse pass is skipped. Now, source dir contains most
recent files/dirs but not new files/dirs, id est files/dirs which it had not
before, while dest dir contains all its previous contents updated and more it
has new files/dirs that were in source dir. If you modify files in the dest,
they will update old one in source, but new files/dirs won't be copied. Normally
you will modify only source, and maybe you will copy also other files from
somewhere to dest, so dest become a backup-hotchpotch/soup. Maybe you will
synchronize also other (source)dir versus the same (dest)dir with this
mode/option.


   The synchronization could be repeated manually (running ES again or
interacting with ES in some now-undefined way when it stands as commodity) or
automatically (notification hit, not in this beta version), according to what
the user does or specified (maybe you won't wish to update files everytime you
change it/them a bit... and so on; the scenary it's huge)


@{fg highlight}Comparing dates@{fg text}

   Dates are compared using DateStamp, which contains days, hours, minutes and
ticks since a reference date (00:00, 1 May 1978 if I remember well). Instead of
using a given OS function, I wrote my own CompareDate. This function ignores
ticks, so two files have different date if only there is a difference in
minutes, hours or days. More, its behaviour could be modified by specifying some
special mode (eg: MODE 2 is like MODE 0 but with different behaviour of
CompareDate, while MODE 3 is like MODE 1 with the same difference in the
behaviour of CompareDate as in MODE 2 - mode is bit oriented flag...)

   So two file could be seen as different if only they have different days, in
this way maybe in the future a more complete ES version (no beta one) will
synchronize dirs only after a longer time, exspecialy when working as cmdty...


@ENDNODE


